Project: Investigate TMDb Movie Dataset¶

Table of Contents¶

  • Introduction

  • Exploratory Data Analysis
  • Conclusions

Introduction¶

This project will be investigating the TMDb movie dataset. The dataset contains information about 10,000 movie titles. Focus of this analysis will be on finding trends in terms of production cost of movie over time across the different genres, and how they relate to success, popularity. The dataset contains key features: "origiginal_title" holds the title for each movie; "genres" is the category each movie; "budget" is the production cost for each movie; "revenue" is amount the amount for each movie grossed; "release_year" is the year each movie was released; "popularity" is the rating for each movie. Quick overview of the dataset indicates 10866 records across 21 columns spanning between year 1960 and 2015.

The questions anaysis will answer are:

1: How does cost of movie production trend across the different genres?¶

2: What period saw significant rise in spending ?¶

3a: What are the ten most popular genres in the last ten years?¶

3b: What genre produced most popular movies during the last ten years?¶

3c: Do popular genres generate high revenue?¶

Data Cleaning¶

Columns with significant null or missing values are "homepage" 7930, "tagline"2824, "keywords"1493,and "production_companies" 1030.These are not useful columns and will be dropped. Genres has 23 sample as null or missing values. The ratio is negligible considering the total sample size. So, genres will be modified to exclude these missing values.

Budget has 5674 rows with zeroes while revenue has 5993 rows exceeding budget values by 320 count of zeros. Of those zeros, 4701 are rows that have zero for budget and revenue. I consider these zero values to be "not reported" or "not available", and as such will exclude them from analysis to avoid skewing correlation and/or distribution.

Conclusions can be drawn that the zeros are due to unavaiable data at the time of collection. Note: "Alvin and the Chipmunks" production was completed on a budget of $60M in 2007, but dataset reflects zero.

Conclusions:¶

The inference drawn from this analysis are not expressed as statistical conclusion as no specific causation have been established. The analysis was performed on dataset which contained some untrue values that resulted in their exclusion, thus, impacting sample size. As a result, the findings are published as observation of the relationship and behavior amongst the variables, where applicable, but not causation. It is important to note that the variables "budget" and "revenue" contained outliers which were not excluded from analysis.

Conclusion 1: How does cost of movie production trend over the years?

The overall view indicated that budget for movies trended upward from the earlier period of the dataset to significantly higher values in the later period. The lowest budget of 6000 occurred in 1960 while the most budget spent, $425m occurred in 2010.

Conclusion 2: What period saw significant rise in spending ?

The analysis observed that significantly higher than average budget was observed in 1997 when budget hit three billion dollars mark and continue to rise to its highest in 2010. Overall, the period between 1997 and 2015 experienced high budget for movie production.

Conclusion 3a: What are the ten most popular genres in the last ten years?

The ten most popular genre during the 2005-2015 period are Action, Adventure, Drama, Comedy, Science Fiction, Animation,Thriller, Fantasy, Crime, and Romance. The genres were measured by their population scores for that period.

Conclusion 3b: What genre produced most popular movies during the last ten years?

Action genre made 129 popular movies between 2005 and 2015. Drama, Comedy, Adventure and Animation fall into top 5 category. The least popular genre is Western with one popular movie during the period. Observation showed that genres with higher number of movies tend to be popular, indicating a positive association between the number of movie made and the popularity score.

Conclusion 3c: Do popular genres generate high revenue?

The analysis observed that genres with higher popularity score acrued more revenue than movies with lower populairty score. There appear to be a positive association between popularity and revenue.
